Jobs and Cron Job (Video - 2:21 - 2:39)

A Job runs a workload until it finishes successfully. 

A CronJob runs a Job automatically on a regular schedule.Unlike Deployments or ReplicaSets that keep apps running forever, Jobs and 
CronJobs are built for tasks that have a clear beginning and end.

1. Jobs
A Job creates one or more Pods and ensures that a target number of them complete successfully. Once the task finishes, the Pod stops 
running and goes into a completed state so you can inspect the logs.

Best for: One-time tasks like data migrations, database backups, or batch processing.
Self-Healing: If a Pod fails before finishing, the Job will start a new one to try again.

Job YAML Example

apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: Job
metadata:
  name: data-cleaner
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: cleaner
        image: alpine
        command: ["echo", "Data cleaning complete!"]
      restartPolicy: Never # Required: Prevents the container from looping forever
  backoffLimit: 4         # Number of retries before marking the Job as failed

2. CronJobs
A CronJob manages Jobs using a time-based schedule. It is exactly like the traditional Linux crontab tool, but it runs tasks inside a 
Kubernetes cluster.

Best for: Recurring tasks like weekly reports, nightly database cleanups, or hourly status checks.
The Schedule Format: It uses five fields to set the time: Minute Hour Day-of-month Month Day-of-week. For example, 0 0 * * * means "every
night at midnight."

CronJob YAML Example

apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: nightly-backup
spec:
  schedule: "0 0 * * *"   # ⏰ Runs every single night at midnight
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: backup
            image: alpine
            command: ["echo", "Backup finished!"]
          restartPolicy: OnFailure

Useful Commands

Run a CronJob manually right now: 

kubectl create job --from=cronjob/nightly-backup manual-backup-run
See running Jobs: kubectl get jobs
See scheduled CronJobs: kubectl get cronjobs

Storage (Video 2:40 - 3:03)

A Volume is a temporary storage folder tied to a single Pod. 
A Persistent Volume is long-term storage that stays safe even if the Pod is completely deleted.

1. Volumes (Episodic Storage)A standard Kubernetes volume lives inside a single Pod. Containers in that Pod can share files through it.

Life Span: It lasts exactly as long as the Pod. If the container crashes, the files stay safe. If the Pod is deleted, the files are gone
forever.
Common Type: emptyDir is a blank folder created when a Pod starts. It is great for quick scratch space or temporary caches.

2. Persistent Volumes (Long-Term Storage)For important data like databases, you need storage that lives outside of any Pod. 
Kubernetes uses a two-part system to handle this:

PersistentVolume (PV): A piece of storage set up by an administrator. It connects to real storage like a cloud disk or a local hard drive.
PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC): A request for storage made by a developer. It asks for a specific size (like 10 Gigabytes) and type of access.
Kubernetes automatically matches the claim (PVC) to an available volume (PV).

YAML Manifest Example
This example shows how a developer requests storage using a PVC, and how a Pod uses that claim to store data safely.

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: db-storage-claim
spec:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce       # Can be read and written by a single node
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 10Gi       # Requests 10 Gigabytes of space
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: database-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: mysql
    image: mysql:latest
    volumeMounts:
    - name: secure-data
      mountPath: /var/lib/mysql # Where the storage appears inside the container
  volumes:
  - name: secure-data
    persistentVolumeClaim:
      claimName: db-storage-claim # Connects to the PVC above

Dynamic Provisioning: StorageClassesInstead of making administrators create every single PersistentVolume by hand, Kubernetes can create
them on demand using a StorageClass. When a developer creates a PVC, the StorageClass automatically talks to your cloud provider 
(like AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud) to create the disk instantly.

Services (3:03 - 3:13)

A Service is a permanent network address that points to a group of running Pods. Because Pods are constantly created and destroyed, 
their internal IP addresses change all the time. A Service gives you a stable IP address and DNS name so other apps can always find them.

Core Functions

Stable Networking: Provides a fixed IP that never changes.
Load Balancing: Distributes incoming traffic evenly across all matching Pods.
Service Discovery: Allows Pods to find each other easily using simple DNS names.

The 4 Service Types

Kubernetes offers four ways to expose your application network:

ClusterIP (Default): Exposes the Service on an internal IP. It makes the app reachable only from inside the cluster.
NodePort: Opens a specific port (usually between 30000–32767) on every single Node. This makes the app reachable from outside the cluster
using any Node's IP address.
LoadBalancer: Connects to your cloud provider (like AWS or Google Cloud) to create a real internet-facing load balancer.
ExternalName: Maps a Kubernetes Service to an external DNS name (like my-database.com) instead of matching Pods.

YAML Manifest ExampleThis example shows a ClusterIP Service that uses a selector to find and route traffic to web frontend Pods:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: frontend-service
spec:
  type: ClusterIP          # 🌐 Accessible only inside the cluster
  selector:
    app: web-frontend      # 🔍 Sends traffic to Pods with this label
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    port: 80               # 🔌 The port the Service listens on
    targetPort: 8080       # 🚀 The actual port running inside the Pod container

How it Works: 
EndpointsWhen you create a Service with a selector, Kubernetes automatically creates an internal helper object called an Endpoint. The 
Endpoint keeps a live list of the changing IP addresses of all healthy Pods that match your selector labels. When a Pod dies, Kubernetes
removes its IP from the Endpoint list instantly so no traffic is lost.


