Ingress (3:24 - 3:44)

An Ingress is an API object that manages external access to the services in a cluster, typically HTTP and HTTPS [1]. It acts as a smart
entry point or reverse proxy, sitting in front of your Services to route incoming internet traffic based on domain names or URL paths
[1, 2].
While a LoadBalancer Service creates a costly cloud load balancer for every single application, an Ingress lets you use just one
single entry point to route traffic to dozens of different internal apps [1].

Ingress vs. Ingress Controller
To use Ingress, you need two distinct components in your cluster [3]:Ingress Resource: The configuration file (the YAML manifest) where
you write your routing rules [1, 3].Ingress Controller: The actual software that reads those rules and moves the traffic [3]. Kubernetes
does not include a controller by default [3]. You must install a popular one like NGINX Ingress Controller, Traefik, or Emissary-ingress
[3].

YAML Manifest Example

This example shows how an Ingress resource takes internet traffic for mywebsite.com and splits it up. It sends traffic for /analytics to 
one backend service and all other traffic to a frontend service [1]

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: main-ingress
  annotations:
    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/rewrite-target: / # Tells the controller how to handle paths
spec:
  ingressClassName: nginx                         # Specifies which controller should read this
  rules:
  - host: mywebsite.com                           # 🌐 Matches the domain name
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /analytics                          # 🛤️ Path rule 1
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: analytics-service
            port:
              number: 80
      - path: /                                   # 🛤️ Path rule 2 (Catch-all)
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: frontend-service
            port:
              number: 80

Key Benefits of Ingress

Cost Savings: You share one cloud load balancer among many internal cluster services [1].
Path-Based Routing: Send traffic to different apps based on the URL path (like /api vs /images) [1].
Host-Based Routing: Route traffic based on different domain names (like site-a.com vs site-b.com) [1].
Secure Connections (SSL/TLS): You can centralise your security certificates at the Ingress level to secure your websites easily [1, 2].

Annotations in Kubernetes (3:44 - 3:47)

Annotations are key-value pairs used to attach non-identifying metadata to Kubernetes objects.

Unlike labels, which Kubernetes uses to group and select resources, annotations are not used to filter or select objects. Instead, they 
are used to store extra background information that tools, libraries, or system administrators can read.

Common Use Cases

Annotations are highly flexible and usually serve these purposes:

Tool Configuration: Telling external tools how to handle the object. For example, telling an Ingress controller specific traffic rules or 
telling a backup tool to ignore a volume.
Release Details: Storing tracking information like build numbers, release dates, or git commit hashes.
Contact Information: Listing the specific team, email address, or Slack channel responsible for the resource.
Audit Tracking: Recording who modified the resource last or what tool created it.

YAML Manifest Example
This example shows a Deployment that uses annotations to store contact info, build data, and a configuration rule for a monitoring tool:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: billing-app
  annotations:
    deployment.kubernetes.io/revision: "1"
    owner: "finance-team@company.com"         # 👥 Team contact info
    buildNumber: "release-v2.1.0-build45"     # 🚀 CI/CD tracking info
    prometheus.io/scrape: "true"              # 📊 Config instruction for monitoring tools
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: billing
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: billing
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: billing-service
        image: billing:v2.1.0

Useful Commands
You can add, update, or view annotations straight from the terminal:
Add an annotation: kubectl annotate pods my-pod-name icon-url="http://example.com"
Overwrite an existing annotation: kubectl annotate pods my-pod-name icon-url="http://example.com" --overwrite
View annotations: Look for the Annotations: section when you run kubectl describe pod my-pod-name.
